''For the 1930s boxer Eligio Sardiñas Montalvo, better known by the nickname "Kid Chocolate," see [[Kid Chocolate]].

'''Peter Quillin''' (born June 22, 1983 in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]]) raised in [[Grand Rapids]], [[Michigan]], and currently resides in [[New York City]] is an undefeated American professional boxer of Cuban descent and the current [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] [[Middleweight]] Champion.<ref>http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Peter_Quillin</ref> He's trained by 4-time trainer of the year [[Freddie Roach (boxing)|Freddie Roach]].<ref>http://www.maxboxing.com/news/max-boxing-news/from-brooklyn-to-la-and-everywhere-in-between-introducing-peter-quillin</ref> Quillin is signed to [[Oscar de la Hoya|Oscar de la Hoya's]] [[Golden Boy Promotions]].<ref>http://www.goldenboypromotions.com/fighters/peter-quillen-kid-chocolate/</ref> He is not to be confused with [[Kid Chocolate]], the late Cuban boxer with whom Quillin shares nicknames.

==Amateur career==
During his amateur boxing career he had 15 fights.<ref>http://www.maxboxing.com/news/other-boxing-news/quillin-used-torture-machine-to-prep-for-brinkley</ref>

===Nickname===
Quillin's father was born and raised in [[Cuba]]. Peter was given the nickname of former World Champion, [[Cuba]]n [[Kid Chocolate]] due to their physical resemblance and Quillin's [[Cuba]]n heritage.

==Professional career==
The tall aggressive Quillin turned pro in New York and signed with Cedric Kushner. He had most of his fights on television flaunting one-punch knockout power in either hands that built him a huge following.

In April 2008, Quillin dominated former contender [[Antwun Echols]].

On June 11, 2008, Peter defeated Dionisio Miranda by unanimous decision at the [[Hard rock]] in [[New York City]]. Quillin won most of the early rounds of the fight and was cruising Miranda in the seventh round. Peter would recover well in the eight round, after being caught by Dionisio. Then Quillin fought the last two rounds of the fight effectively, with the final judges’ scores being 97-92, 97-92 and 97-93.<ref>{{cite web
  | last =Lieberman
  | first =Michael
  | title = Quillin Defeats Miranda, Fails To Impress
  | publisher =BoxingNews24.com
  | date =2008-06-13
  | url =http://www.boxingnews24.com/2008/06/quillin-defeats-miranda-fails-to-impress/
  | accessdate =2008-06-14 }}</ref>

In April 2010, Peter moved from [[New York City]] to [[Los Angeles]] to train with 4-time trainer of the year [[Freddie Roach (boxing)|Freddie Roach]].<ref>http://www.eastsideboxing.com/news.php?p=23659&more=1</ref>

On April 29, 2011, Quillin stopped title contender [[Jesse Brinkley]] to win the vacant United States Boxing Organisation [[Super Middleweight]] Championship in [[Reno, Nevada]].<ref>http://www.goldenboypromotions.com/news/94b093e4b7a4d3457270c01ae621b6e9/</ref> This bout was televised as the main-event by [[TeleFutura]].<ref>http://www.therewillbebloodfightshow.com/2011/04/jesse-brinkley-vs-peter-quillin-press.html</ref>

On July 23, 2011, Quillin rolled past late substitute [[Jason LeHoullier]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. He laid a beating on LeHoullier, hitting him cleanly with both hands throughout the fight. Although there were no knockdowns, LeHoullier was outclassed.<ref>http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/6792080/peter-quillin-dominates-jason-lehoullier-5th-round-tko</ref>

On November 5, 2011, Quillin made an impressive HBO Debut, stopping Craig McEwan in the 6th round in Cancun, Mexico. Then in June 2012 he fought Winky Wright, winning by unanimous decision and making Wright retire.

